        <section>
            <h2>What is the RAD Model?</h2>
            <p>
                The Rapid Application Development (RAD) Model is a software development approach that focuses on building applications quickly through iterative development and continuous user feedback. Instead of following a strict sequence of steps, RAD emphasizes flexibility and rapid prototyping, allowing developers to quickly create working versions of the software and refine them based on user input. This makes it especially useful for projects where speed and adaptability are important.
            </p>
        </section>

        <img src="img/rad.jpg" alt="RAD Model Image" class="rad-image">

        <section>
            <h2>How the RAD Process Works</h2>
            <p>
                The RAD Model is divided into four main phases. First, requirements planning is completed through collaboration between developers and users to define the system’s goals. Next, during the user design phase, prototypes are created and continuously improved based on feedback. In the construction phase, developers build and refine the software using fast development tools. Finally, the cutover phase includes testing, integration, and deployment of the final product. These phases often overlap and repeat, allowing for quick adjustments and improvements throughout development.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Advantages and Use Cases</h2>
            <p>
                The RAD Model is ideal for projects that require fast delivery and frequent updates. It allows teams to quickly respond to user feedback and adapt to changing requirements. This approach improves user satisfaction and helps catch issues early through continuous testing and prototyping. However, RAD requires skilled developers and active user involvement, and it may not be suitable for very large or complex systems. It works best for small to medium-sized projects with clearly defined goals and flexible requirements. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
            </p>
        </section>

